    "analysis": "Previous step loaded all telemetry and produced compact global summaries (counts and global P95) for metric, trace, and log files. Observations: metric/trace/log data are abundant inside the incident window (metric_window_count=8975, trace_window_count=18464, log_window_count=2182). error_logs.csv appears empty. The summaries show many service-level KPIs including candidate services (e.g., ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-travel-service, etc.). Next we must follow the preprocess -> anomaly detection -> fault identification -> localization flow and focus on the provided possible root-cause components (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service). To narrow candidates, we should identify metric anomalies for these five services: compute global thresholds (P95 and P05) per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using full series (not filtered), then inspect data within the incident window for abnormalities (high >P95 and low <=P05). Return compact aggregates: counts of anomalous points, earliest anomaly time, and severity (max/min) per component-KPI so we can pick candidates for trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For metric.csv, restrict analysis only to cmdb_id in [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"]. For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) do the following: 1) Using the full available series (no time filter) compute global P95 and global P05 of 'value'. 2) Filter metric rows to the incident window 2024-01-25 16:19:12 to 2024-01-25 16:49:12 UTC. 3) For the filtered rows compute: total_points_in_window, count_high_anom = number of rows with value > global_P95, earliest_high_ts (UTC) if count_high_anom>0, max_value_in_window; count_low_anom = number of rows with value <= global_P05, earliest_low_ts (UTC) if count_low_anom>0, min_value_in_window. 4) Produce a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, p05, total_points_in_window, count_high_anom, earliest_high_ts, max_value_in_window, count_low_anom, earliest_low_ts, min_value_in_window. Only include rows where total_points_in_window>0. Sort by (count_high_anom+count_low_anom) descending and limit output to top 50 rows. Return the table."}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global thresholds and inspected metric anomalies for the five candidate services during the incident window. Results: 35 component-KPI series had data in-window; ts-auth-service shows the most widespread anomalies across multiple KPIs (cpu, mem, diskio, latency-50/90, socket, workload) with several points breaching global P95 and P05 (earliest notable high cpu at 2024-01-25T16:30:00Z and other anomalies spread across ~16:22–16:37Z). Other services (ts-train-service, ts-travel-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service) also show some anomalies but with fewer KPIs affected. From metrics alone ts-auth-service is the top candidate, but several services show concurrent anomalies at different times, so we must use traces to determine which faulty service is the most downstream faulty component in call chains and whether trace-level error_rate/duration spikes point to a root cause. No error_logs rows were present to inspect. Next we should analyze traces to see if traces to ts-auth-service (and the other candidate services) exhibit elevated error_rate or duration within the window and the earliest anomaly times to correlate with metrics.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "In trace.csv, select trace rows whose trace_name contains any of: 'to_ts-auth-service','to_ts-order-service','to_ts-route-service','to_ts-train-service','to_ts-travel-service'. For each unique trace_name compute: (A) global P95 and P05 of 'value' using the full available series (no time filtering); (B) then filter trace rows to the incident window 2024-01-25 16:19:12 to 2024-01-25 16:49:12 UTC and compute: total_points_in_window, count_high_anom = number of rows with value > global_P95, earliest_high_ts (UTC) if any, max_value_in_window, count_low_anom = number of rows with value <= global_P05, earliest_low_ts (UTC) if any, min_value_in_window. Return a compact table with columns: trace_name, metric_type (extract suffix like duration_mean/duration_p95/error_rate/row_count), p95, p05, total_points_in_window, count_high_anom, earliest_high_ts, max_value_in_window, count_low_anom, earliest_low_ts, min_value_in_window. Sort by (count_high_anom+count_low_anom) desc and limit output to top 20 rows."}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis (previous step) inspected calls to the five candidate services and found: duration spikes concentrated around ~16:35 UTC for order/travel/route services, and row_count peaks around ~16:25–16:35 UTC. trace.error_rate is zero across the window, so failures are not reflected as trace error rates. ts-auth-service shows metric anomalies across many resource KPIs but fewer trace anomalies (smaller series). Interpretation so far: this appears to be a performance/throughput issue (latency/row_count spikes) rather than elevated error rates. Multiple services exhibit anomalies, so to localize the root cause we must (1) use traces to determine which faulty service is the most downstream faulty service in call chains and (2) use logs to identify the resource-level failure reason (CPU/memory/socket/disk/network). We do not yet have evidence to pick a single downstream faulty service as the root cause because several services (order, travel, route) show strong duration/row_count anomalies around the same time window. Next step: examine logs for the five candidate services (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service) to see whether any show log-level signs (error counts, socket errors, or other log KPIs) that correlate with the metric/trace anomalies and indicate a cause (e.g., socket errors suggesting network issues, or rising error_count suggesting failures).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "In log.csv, restrict to cmdb_id in [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"]. For each unique (cmdb_id, log_name): 1) compute global P95 and P05 of 'value' using the full series (no filtering); 2) filter log rows to the incident window 2024-01-25 16:19:12 to 2024-01-25 16:49:12 UTC; 3) compute compact aggregates: total_points_in_window, count_high_anom = number of rows with value > p95, earliest_high_ts (UTC) if any, max_value_in_window, count_low_anom = number of rows with value <= p05, earliest_low_ts (UTC) if any, min_value_in_window. Return a table with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, p95, p05, total_points_in_window, count_high_anom, earliest_high_ts, max_value_in_window, count_low_anom, earliest_low_ts, min_value_in_window. Sort by (count_high_anom+count_low_anom) desc and limit output to top 20 rows." }

