    "instruction": "Filter metric.csv to cmdb_id == \"ts-order-service\". For each kpi_name compute global P95 and P05 using the full series (no time filtering). Then filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-25 16:19:12 to 2024-01-25 16:49:12 UTC and compute: total_points_in_window, count_high_anom (value > p95), earliest_high_ts (UTC) if any, max_value_in_window, breach_ratio_high = (max_value_in_window - p95)/p95 if count_high_anom>0 else 0; count_low_anom (value <= p05), earliest_low_ts if any, min_value_in_window, breach_ratio_low = (p05 - min_value_in_window)/p05 if count_low_anom>0 else 0. Return a compact table with columns: kpi_name, p95, p05, total_points_in_window, count_high_anom, earliest_high_ts, max_value_in_window, breach_ratio_high, count_low_anom, earliest_low_ts, min_value_in_window, breach_ratio_low. Sort by breach_ratio_high descending and limit output to top 20 rows." }

{
    "analysis": "We reviewed metrics, traces, and logs for the five candidate services inside the incident window. Findings so far: (1) trace durations and row_count indicate throughput and latency spikes concentrated around ~16:25–16:35 UTC for ts-order-service, ts-travel-service, and ts-route-service; (2) trace.error_rate and log.error_count are zero, so this is a performance/throughput incident rather than increased request failures; (3) ts-auth-service shows widespread resource KPI anomalies (cpu, mem, socket, workload) with some anomalies appearing earlier (~16:22–16:30 UTC) than the major latency spikes in downstream services (~16:35 UTC). Per the fault-identification and root-localization rules, the root cause should be the earliest and most significant faulty component at the same level, or the most downstream faulty service within trace call chains. Current results show multiple services with modest breaches (commonly ~20% above P95), none with an extreme breach >50% that would unambiguously identify a root cause by severity alone. However, timestamps indicate ts-auth-service anomalies occurred earlier than the major downstream latency spikes, making it a candidate causal source. To decide between (a) ts-auth-service resource degradation causing downstream latency, or (b) a traffic surge affecting order/travel/route causing latencies locally, we need a compact comparison: for each of the five candidate services, determine the earliest high-anomaly timestamp (first value > global P95 across all KPIs) and the maximum relative breach (max((value-p95)/p95) among in-window anomalies) to find which service had the earliest and most severe anomaly.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For each cmdb_id in [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"]: 1) For every kpi_name compute global P95 using the full metric series (no time filtering). 2) Filter metric rows to the incident window 2024-01-25 16:19:12 to 2024-01-25 16:49:12 UTC. 3) For each cmdb_id compute: earliest_high_ts = the earliest timestamp in-window where value > that KPI's global P95 (across all KPIs), and max_breach = the maximum over all in-window points and KPIs of (value - KPI_P95)/KPI_P95 (use 0 if no high anomalies). 4) Return a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, earliest_high_ts (UTC, NaT if none), max_breach (float), and number_of_high_anomalous_kpis (count of distinct KPIs that had any value > P95 in-window). Sort rows by earliest_high_ts ascending (NaT last). Limit output to these 5 rows." }

Based on the metric/trace/log correlation (earliest workload spike on ts-order-service at ~16:25 UTC, trace latency peaks ~16:35 UTC, and memory above baseline), the most likely root cause is resource pressure on ts-order-service manifested as elevated memory usage and resulting performance degradation.

